availability.p: This resource has been designed for free consultation in association with the Sloane Consortium of UK national institutions which hold the original manuscript catalogue documents and related collections of Sir Hans Sloane. All content is reproducible as long as the source is indicated by referencing the publication and the name of the institutional owner of the original catalogue manuscript -- in this case The British Library.

notesStmt.note: An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane’s Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI: http://doi.org/10.16995/olh.409 The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. These transcriptions were then fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team that is also responsible for the complete TEI markup of the transcriptions.

msItem.colophon: Sloane MS 3972B is a bound manuscript volume containing a catalogue of manuscripts which were collected by Hans Sloane (1660-1753) between 1680 and 1753. Sloane's manuscript collections were originally catalogued alongside his book collections in the volumes now bound as Sloane MS 3972 C, however, many folios recording the acquisition of these manuscripts were removed by the British Museum Trustees sometime after 1753 to form a then newly bound and constituted catalogue now called Sloane MS 3972B. The posthumous separation of these materials from Sloane’s own original comprehensive catalogue has resulted in this Sloane MS 3972B catalogue being very different to Sloane MS 3972C in its structure and style, which often vary from folio to folio. The different type of descriptive language required by the cataloguing of manuscripts as opposed to printed books is also noticeable. The catalogue contains a diversity of languages and, like Sloane MS 3972C vol. VI, it is written in a number of hands, including that of Sloane himself.

Hans Sloane resided in Bloomsbury Square, London and later at the Chelsea Manor House. His collecting activities spanned the early modern and Enlightenment periods and are global in scope. A physician and President of the Royal Society, he was an influential figure in the intellectual developments of his time both in England and Europe. At his death his will stipulated that his collections should be bought by the State for the purposes of creating a public Museum, thereby creating the British Museum in 1753. Since that time, Sloane's collections have been divided between the British Museum, The British Library and the Natural History Museum (London), which institutions still retain most of his collections and catalogues. The provenance of these manuscript catalogues is therefore direct and accountable. Sloane did not publish these catalogues of his collection in his lifetime, and these digital scholarly editions created by the Enlightenment Architectures project are the first ever publications of any of these catalogues.

It is estimated that Sloane made at least 50 catalogues of the various parts of his collection, including his Natural History collections and Library. The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. The transcription of this catalogue, MS3972B, has not been as fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team as Fossils I or Miscellanea or MS 3972 C VI; instead it has very basic mark up such as pencil and underline. An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane’s Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI: Further information and further reading about his collections and catalogues can be found on the Reconstructing Sloane website and on the websites of the institutions he founded and which have contributed to this research project: The British Museum, The British Library, The Natural History Museum (London) and those in which he was closely involved, such as The Royal Society.

projectDesc.p: Text encoded for the Enlightenment Architectures project: texts of Sir Hans Sloane’s catalogues of his collections encoded with TEI, aiming to provide a collection of prime exemplar TEI encoded materials for this early modern collection management ‘paper tool’ (A Leverhulme Trust funded research project).
